GAN Fixing¶

Elias Mann and Mark Brubaker

Introduction¶

In this project we applied different heuristic methods to improve image generation for WGAN-GP. For with project, we used 2 classes from cifar10: boats and planes to train our GANs. We started by adjusting the architecture of the generator and discriminator to use one-hot encoded the class labels. Next we apply the 3 differnent heuristic methods from Andrew Brock's Paper and Tim Saliman's Paper on improving GANs - detailed below. We run then GANs until we get resonable images - or until we believe running more epochs would be futile - then calculate the "Inception score". Well, its more like a "VGG score" because use VGG16 pretrained on ImageNet to calculate the score.

We have code with image outputs below but I will also bring the images up here for readability.

WGAN-GP without Heuristics¶

Starting with the WGAN-GP without any heuristic methods, we find that we can generate reasonable images in 500 epochs and have an "Inception" score of 1.350248098373413. This took about 6 seconds per epoch or about 50 minutes to train on Mark's Laptop with an NVIDIA RTX 3070.


Which brings us to our heuristics...

Spectral Normalization¶

We start by adding spectral normalization. Spectral normalization is a normalization method that is applied to the discriminator of the network. This method normalizes the maximum singular value of the weight matrix of the discriminator which contrains the matrix's Lipschitz constant - a measure of how much the output of a finction can change with respect to its input. This normalization process makes the discriminator less sensitive to small changes in the input images this stabilizes training and improves the image quality of the generator... Supposedly. We expected this to improve image generation and "Inception" score because as shown in Andrew Brock's Paper, adding this heuristic did improve their results when training with SA-GAN (Zhang et al., 2018). We were wrong. The generated images were incomprehensible and the "Inception" score decreased to 1.1171541213989258. We ran this model for 500 epochs which took about 5 seconds per epoch or about 45 minutes. Training was slightly fastter than the basic GAN. Unfortunately, We simply could not get decent images.


Perhaps training the model longer would achieve better results. We stopped training after 500 epochs because with a train time difference of only 1 second per epoch, we believed that an equivalent number of epochs would be sufficient to achieve comperable results to the basic GAN, if the new heuristic was effective. Therefore with poor results after 500 epochs, we declare the heuristic ineffective for our dataset.

Another reason that spectral normalization could have yielded poor results is that the images in our dataset are largely similar. Boats and planes are typically similar colors - grey, black, white - and have a blue backgrounds - sky and water. Additionally, due to physical contraints, planes largely must conform to similar shapes to be able to fly, and boats must conform to similar shapes in order to float. Since constraining the Lipschitz constant for the discriminator's weight matrix makes it less sensitive to small changes in the input data, maybe it was unable to learn the minor differences in the labels we chose.

Hinge Loss¶

The next heurstic we tried adding was hinge loss. Hinge loss is a type of loss function in the discriminatoe of the network. Hinge loss is similar to cross entropy however it prioritizes correct classification for samples that are more difficult to classify which is useful in cases where the data is imbalanced. With hinge loss, the loss is only computeed for examples where the discriminator predicts incorrectly, or the prediction is near the descision boundary. This loss function can improve the stability of the model expecially when labels are unbalanced. Our dataset is perfectly balanced between boats and plans but since hinge loss does improve stability, we still expected better results. based on the images below, we percieve slightly better images than the basic GAN with an "Inception" score of 1.435945987701416, which is slightly better than the basic GAN. We ran this model for 500 epochs which took about 6 seconds per epoch, or 50 minutes which is about the same as the basic GAN.

Minibatch Discrimination with Hinge Loss¶

For our final heuristic, we used minibatch discrimination as well as hinge loss. Minibatch discrimination is a technique that allows the disriminator to process multiple examples from the data, rather than just one at a time. This is used to prevent mode collapse - when a generator only produces a very limited set of images. One of the causes of mode collapse is thatt the discriminator learns to distinguish between the fake and real images based on only a few features like color or texture. Training with mutiple examplies in compination allows the discriminator to learn more complex patterns and relationships in the images which forces the generator to produce more realistic images. We expected better results from this heuristic which was not necessarily the case. To our eyes, the generated images were slightly better than those geneerated using only hinge loss noweer the difference is marginal. However the "Inception" score was only 1.3703337907791138 which is worse then the hinge loss GAN, but better than the basic GAN. We ran this model for 500 epochs which took about 9 seconds per epoch, or an hour and 15 minutes which is the longest training time for any of our models.

def make_grid(images):
    num_images = 32
    height = 4
    width = num_images // height

    size = images.shape[1]
    grid = np.zeros((height * size, width * size, 3))

    # Get the total number of images in img_batches
    total_images = images.shape[0]

    # if the number of images is less than the number of images we want to display
    # then we will just display all the images
    if total_images < num_images:
        num_images = total_images

    for i in range(height):
        for j in range(width):
            idx = i * width + j

            if idx >= num_images:
                break

            # Get the image from the batch
            im = images[idx, :, :, :]

            # Reshape the image into a square
            im = im.reshape((size, size, 3))

            # Add the image to the grid
            grid[i * size:(i + 1) * size, j * size:(j + 1) * size, :] = im

    # Normalize the grid values to the range [0, 1] for displaying
    grid = (grid - grid.min()) / (grid.max() - grid.min())

    return grid

def plot_grid(grid, title=None):

    # Create a figure with double the DPI
    plt.figure(dpi=2.5 * plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'])

    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title, fontsize=5)
        
    plt.imshow(grid)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

grid = make_grid(train_dataset.take(1).as_numpy_iterator().next()[0])
plot_grid(grid, title="CIFAR-10 Dataset Vehicles")

latent_dim = 128
size = 32
channels = 3
num_classes = len(np.unique(train_labels))
print(f"Number of classes: {num_classes}")
# print the  number of labels per class and the class labels
print(f"Number of labels per class: {np.unique(train_labels, return_counts=True)[1]}")
print(f"Class labels: {np.unique(train_labels)}")

generator_in_channels = latent_dim + num_classes
discriminator_in_channels = channels + num_classes
print(generator_in_channels, discriminator_in_channels)


# this model originally from https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/generative/dcgan 
# manipulated to have different sizing possible
def make_generator_model():
    noise_input = layers.Input(shape=(latent_dim,))
    label_input = layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32')
    
    # Embed the label input and reshape it
    label_embedding = layers.Embedding(num_classes, latent_dim)(label_input)
    label_embedding = layers.Reshape((latent_dim,))(label_embedding)
    
    # Concatenate the noise input and label embedding
    combined_input = layers.Concatenate()([noise_input, label_embedding])
    
    int_size_4 = int(size/4)
    x = layers.Dense(int_size_4 * int_size_4 * 256, use_bias=False)(combined_input)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)

    x = layers.Reshape((int_size_4, int_size_4, 256))(x)

    x = layers.Conv2DTranspose(128, (5, 5), strides=(1, 1), padding='same', use_bias=False)(x)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    
    x = layers.UpSampling2D(size=(2, 2), interpolation='nearest')(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', use_bias=False)(x)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)

    x = layers.UpSampling2D(size=(2, 2), interpolation='nearest')(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(channels, (3, 3), padding='same', use_bias=False, activation='tanh')(x)

    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[noise_input, label_input], outputs=x)
    
    return model

def make_discriminator_model():
    image_input = layers.Input(shape=(size, size, channels))
    label_input = layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32')
    
    # Embed the label input and reshape it
    label_embedding = layers.Embedding(num_classes, size * size)(label_input)
    label_embedding = layers.Reshape((size, size, 1))(label_embedding)
    
    # Concatenate the image input and label embedding along the channel axis
    combined_input = layers.Concatenate(axis=-1)([image_input, label_embedding])
    
    x = layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(combined_input)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(1)(x)
    
    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[image_input, label_input], outputs=x)
    
    return model

# Define the loss functions for the discriminator,
# which should be (fake_loss - real_loss).
# We will add the gradient penalty later to this loss function.
def discriminator_loss(real_img, fake_img):
    real_loss = tf.reduce_mean(real_img)
    fake_loss = tf.reduce_mean(fake_img)
    return fake_loss - real_loss # minimize (slides have max in them)


# Define the loss functions for the generator.
def generator_loss(fake_img):
    return -tf.reduce_mean(fake_img) # minimize (slides have max in them)

#---------------------------
# params from WGAN-GP paper
#---------------------------
# Loss weight for gradient penalty
lambda_gp = 10

generator_optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(
    learning_rate=0.0002, beta_1=0.5, beta_2=0.9
)
discriminator_optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(
    learning_rate=0.0002, beta_1=0.5, beta_2=0.9
)

# Fine tuned vgg for use in inception score

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

# Load pre-trained VGG model without the top layers
vgg_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(32, 32, 3))

# Freeze the layers
for layer in vgg_base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Add a custom top layer for the 2 classes (boats and planes)
x = tf.keras.layers.Flatten()(vgg_base.output)
x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
predictions = tf.keras.layers.Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)

# Create the fine-tuned VGG model
vgg_finetuned = Model(inputs=vgg_base.input, outputs=predictions)

# Compile the model
vgg_finetuned.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# split the dataset into train and validation 80/20
train_dataset_vgg = train_dataset_prebatch.take(8000)
valid_dataset_vgg = train_dataset_prebatch.skip(8000)

# print the size of the train and validation datasets
print(train_dataset_vgg.cardinality())
print(valid_dataset_vgg.cardinality())

def preprocess_data(image, label):
    # Convert the labels to one-hot encoded format
    label = tf.one_hot(label, depth=2)

    label = tf.reshape(label, (2,))

    return image, label

# Apply the preprocessing function to the train and validation datasets
train_dataset_vgg = train_dataset_vgg.map(preprocess_data)
valid_dataset_vgg = valid_dataset_vgg.map(preprocess_data)

batch_size = 512
train_dataset_vgg = train_dataset_vgg.batch(batch_size)
valid_dataset_vgg = valid_dataset_vgg.batch(batch_size)

# Fine-tune the VGG model on the preprocessed dataset
vgg_finetuned.fit(train_dataset_vgg, epochs=50, validation_data=valid_dataset_vgg, verbose=0)

# Get the accuracy of the model on the validation dataset
vgg_finetuned.evaluate(valid_dataset_vgg)

from scipy.stats import entropy

def inception_score(gen):
    num_samples = 512
    # Generate a set of images using your trained GAN
    random_noise = tf.random.normal([num_samples, latent_dim])
    random_labels = tf.random.uniform(shape=(num_samples, 1), minval=0, maxval=num_classes, dtype=tf.int32)
    generated_images = gen([random_noise, random_labels], training=False)

    # Rescale the images from [-1, 1] to [0, 1]

    # Get the class probabilities from the fine-tuned VGG model
    predicted_probs = vgg_finetuned.predict(generated_images)

    # Calculate the Inception Score
    scores = []
    for i in range(num_samples):
        scores.append(entropy(predicted_probs[i]))
    is_score = np.exp(np.mean(scores))

    return is_score

Training GAN without Heuristics¶

In [11]:
@tf.function # commenting this as there is some problem with non-eager...
def train_step_basic(images, labels):


    # Train the discriminator first. The original paper recommends training
    # the discriminator for `x` more steps (typically 5) as compared to
    # one step of the generator.
    batch_size = tf.shape(images)[0]

    for i in range(5):

        # Get the latent vector
        noise = tf.random.normal([batch_size, latent_dim])
        generated_labels = tf.random.uniform([batch_size, 1], minval=0, maxval=num_classes, dtype=tf.int32)

        with tf.GradientTape() as disc_tape:

            # Generate fake images from the latent vector
            generated_images = generator([noise, generated_labels], training=True)

            # also get interpolations for the gradient penalty
            alpha = tf.random.normal([batch_size, 1, 1, 1], 0.0, 1.0)
            diff = generated_images - images
            interpolated = images + alpha * diff

            # Get the logits for the fake images
            fake_output = discriminator([generated_images, generated_labels], training=True)

            # Get the logits for the real images
            real_output = discriminator([images, labels], training=True)

            # Calculate the discriminator loss using the fake and real image logits
            disc_loss = discriminator_loss(real_output,fake_output)

            # code from https://keras.io/examples/generative/wgan_gp/
            # Calculate the gradient penalty
            with tf.GradientTape(watch_accessed_variables=False) as gp_tape:
                gp_tape.watch(interpolated) # manually define what to watch
                # 1. Get the discriminator output for this interpolated image.
                pred = discriminator([interpolated, labels], training=True)

            # Calculate the gradients w.r.t to this interpolated image.
            grads = gp_tape.gradient(pred, [interpolated])[0]

            # Calculate the norm of the gradients.
            norm = tf.sqrt(tf.reduce_sum(tf.square(grads), axis=[1, 2, 3]))
            gp = tf.reduce_mean((norm - 1.0) ** 2) # is norm close to 1?

            # Add the gradient penalty to the original discriminator loss
            d_loss = disc_loss + gp * lambda_gp

        # Get the gradients w.r.t the discriminator loss
        gradients_of_discriminator = disc_tape.gradient(d_loss, discriminator.trainable_variables)

        # Update the weights of the discriminator using the discriminator optimizer
        discriminator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_discriminator, discriminator.trainable_variables))



    # Train the generator
    # Get the latent vector
    noise = tf.random.normal([batch_size, latent_dim])
    labels = tf.random.uniform(shape=(batch_size, 1), minval=0, maxval=num_classes, dtype=tf.int32)
    with tf.GradientTape() as gen_tape:
        # Generate fake images using the generator
        generated_images = generator([noise, labels], training=True)
        # Get the discriminator logits for fake images
        fake_output = discriminator([generated_images, labels], training=True)

        # Calculate the generator loss
        gen_loss = generator_loss(fake_output)

    gradients_of_generator = gen_tape.gradient(gen_loss, generator.trainable_variables)
    generator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_generator, generator.trainable_variables))

        start = time.time()
        
        print(f'Epoch {epoch+1}/{EPOCHS}')
        progbar = Progbar(target=len(train_dataset), width=30, verbose=1, interval=0.05)

        for batch_idx, (image_batch, label_batch) in enumerate(train_dataset):
            train_step_basic(image_batch, label_batch)
            progbar.update(batch_idx + 1)

        print('Time for epoch {} is {:.2f} sec'.format(epoch + 1, time.time() - start))

import tensorflow_addons as tfa

def make_discriminator_model_spec_norm():
    image_input = layers.Input(shape=(size, size, channels))
    label_input = layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32')
    
    # Embed the label input and reshape it
    label_embedding = layers.Embedding(num_classes, size * size)(label_input)
    label_embedding = layers.Reshape((size, size, 1))(label_embedding)
    
    # Concatenate the image input and label embedding along the channel axis
    combined_input = layers.Concatenate(axis=-1)([image_input, label_embedding])
    
    x = tfa.layers.SpectralNormalization(layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same'))(combined_input)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = tfa.layers.SpectralNormalization(layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same'))(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(1)(x)
    
    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[image_input, label_input], outputs=x)
    
    return model

Hinge Loss¶

# Define the loss functions for the discriminator using hinge loss
def discriminator_loss(real_img, fake_img):
    real_loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.relu(1.0 - real_img))
    fake_loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.relu(1.0 + fake_img))
    return real_loss + fake_loss

@tf.function # commenting this as there is some problem with non-eager...
def train_step_hinge_loss(images, labels):


    # Train the discriminator first. The original paper recommends training
    # the discriminator for `x` more steps (typically 5) as compared to
    # one step of the generator. Here we will train it for 3 extra steps
    # as compared to 5 to reduce the training time.
    batch_size = tf.shape(images)[0]

    for i in range(5):

        # Get the latent vector
        noise = tf.random.normal([batch_size, latent_dim])
        generated_labels = tf.random.uniform([batch_size, 1], minval=0, maxval=num_classes, dtype=tf.int32)

        with tf.GradientTape() as disc_tape:

            # Generate fake images from the latent vector
            generated_images = generator([noise, generated_labels], training=True)

            # also get interpolations for the gradient penalty
            alpha = tf.random.normal([batch_size, 1, 1, 1], 0.0, 1.0)
            diff = generated_images - images
            interpolated = images + alpha * diff

            # Get the logits for the fake images
            fake_output = discriminator([generated_images, generated_labels], training=True)

            # Get the logits for the real images
            real_output = discriminator([images, labels], training=True)

            # Calculate the discriminator loss using the fake and real image logits
            disc_loss = discriminator_loss(real_output,fake_output)

            # code from https://keras.io/examples/generative/wgan_gp/
            # Calculate the gradient penalty
            with tf.GradientTape(watch_accessed_variables=False) as gp_tape:
                gp_tape.watch(interpolated) # manually define what to watch
                # 1. Get the discriminator output for this interpolated image.
                pred = discriminator([interpolated, labels], training=True)

            # Calculate the gradients w.r.t to this interpolated image.
            grads = gp_tape.gradient(pred, [interpolated])[0]

            # Calculate the norm of the gradients.
            norm = tf.sqrt(tf.reduce_sum(tf.square(grads), axis=[1, 2, 3]))
            gp = tf.reduce_mean((norm - 1.0) ** 2) # is norm close to 1?

            # Add the gradient penalty to the original discriminator loss
            d_loss = disc_loss + gp * lambda_gp

        # Get the gradients w.r.t the discriminator loss
        gradients_of_discriminator = disc_tape.gradient(disc_loss, discriminator.trainable_variables)

        # Update the weights of the discriminator using the discriminator optimizer
        discriminator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_discriminator, discriminator.trainable_variables))



    # Train the generator
    # Get the latent vector
    noise = tf.random.normal([batch_size, latent_dim])
    labels = tf.random.uniform(shape=(batch_size, 1), minval=0, maxval=num_classes, dtype=tf.int32)
    with tf.GradientTape() as gen_tape:
        # Generate fake images using the generator
        generated_images = generator([noise, labels], training=True)
        # Get the discriminator logits for fake images
        fake_output = discriminator([generated_images, labels], training=True)

        # Calculate the generator loss
        gen_loss = generator_loss(fake_output)

    gradients_of_generator = gen_tape.gradient(gen_loss, generator.trainable_variables)
    generator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_generator, generator.trainable_variables))

Minibatch Discrimination¶

In [27]:
# Mini-batch discrimination layer from GPT-4

# The MinibatchDiscrimination layer computes features that help to distinguish real samples from generated samples in a batch. 
# It does so by calculating the L1-norm of the differences between the activations of each pair of samples in the batch. 
# The exponential of the negative L1-norms are then summed to create the minibatch features. 
# These features are then concatenated with the original input tensor to be used in the following layers of the model.
# This allows the discriminator to consider the relationships between samples in a batch. This helps in detecting mode collapse.
class MinibatchDiscrimination(layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, num_kernels, kernel_dim, **kwargs):
        super(MinibatchDiscrimination, self).__init__(**kwargs)
        self.num_kernels = num_kernels
        self.kernel_dim = kernel_dim

    def build(self, input_shape):
        self.T = self.add_weight(name='T', shape=(input_shape[-1], self.num_kernels, self.kernel_dim), initializer='glorot_uniform')

    # Compute the minibatch discrimination features for the input tensor (x)
    def call(self, x):
        # Compute the activation by multiplying the input tensor with the weight tensor
        activation = tf.tensordot(x, self.T, axes=[[1], [0]])

        # Calculate the differences between the activations of each pair of samples in the batch
        diffs = tf.expand_dims(activation, 3) - tf.expand_dims(tf.transpose(activation, perm=[1, 2, 0]), 0)

        # Compute the L1-norm (absolute differences) of the differences tensor
        abs_diffs = tf.reduce_sum(tf.abs(diffs), axis=2)

        # Compute the minibatch features by summing the exponentials of the negative L1-norms
        minibatch_features = tf.reduce_sum(tf.exp(-abs_diffs), axis=2)

        # Concatenate the input tensor with the minibatch features
        return tf.concat([x, minibatch_features], 1)

    def get_config(self):
        config = super(MinibatchDiscrimination, self).get_config()
        config.update({'num_kernels': self.num_kernels, 'kernel_dim': self.kernel_dim})
        return config


def make_discriminator_model_minibatch():
    image_input = layers.Input(shape=(size, size, channels))
    label_input = layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32')

    # Embed the label input and reshape it
    label_embedding = layers.Embedding(num_classes, size * size)(label_input)
    label_embedding = layers.Reshape((size, size, 1))(label_embedding)

    # Concatenate the image input and label embedding along the channel axis
    combined_input = layers.Concatenate(axis=-1)([image_input, label_embedding])

    x = layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(combined_input)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(x)
    x = layers.LeakyReLU()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)

    x = layers.Flatten()(x)

    # Add Minibatch Discrimination layer
    x = MinibatchDiscrimination(num_kernels=64, kernel_dim=5)(x)

    x = layers.Dense(1)(x)

    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[image_input, label_input], outputs=x)

    return model
